Part I: Research Question

  1. One research question we will answer with this analysis is, Are there recurring patterns for seasonal effects in revenue?
  2. The goal of this time series analysis is to utilize the provided data set which includes date and revenue data to study revenue trends over time and understand seasonal fluctuations. This data can be utilized to predict future outcomes.

Part II: Method Justification

  1. An assumption of time series analysis is stationarity. Stationarity refers to when a change in time does not affect a change in the shape of the distribution. Another assumption of time series analysis is autocorrelation. Autocorrelation quantifies how related one data point is to another.

Part IV: Model Identification and Analysis

The annotated findings with visualizations of the data analysis include the following components:
  1. The presence or lack of seasonal component: Seasonality is not present.
  2. Trends: the trend line displays some volatility.
  3. The autocorrelation function demonstrated the data was stationary so we ran diff() to make it stationary.
  4. Spectral density: demonstrates seasonality is not present.
  5. A decomposed time series was run and is shown below.
  6. Confirmation of the lack of trends in the residuals of the decomposed series is shown below.
In[17]:
#testing stationarity
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller
def ad_test(dataset):
    dftest = adfuller(dataset, autolag = 'AIC')
    print("1. ADF: ", dftest[0])
    print("2. P-value: ", dftest[1])
    print("3. Num of Lags:", dftest[2])
    print("4. Num of Obs Used for ADF Regression and Critical Values Calc:", dftest[3])
    print("5. Critical Values: ")
    for key, val in dftest[4].items():
        print("\t",key,": ",val)
        
ad_test(df['Revenue'])

In[19]:
#test for stationarity again
result = adfuller(df_stationary['Revenue'])
print("Test statistics: ", result[0])
print("p-value: ", result[1])
print("critical values: ", result[4])

if result[1]<= 0.05:
    print("Reject null hypothesis, the time series is stationary")
else:
    print("Fail to reject null hypothesis, the time series is non-stationary")

After running diff() we now see that the data is stationary because the p-value is 0.0 which is below the critical value of .05.

Part V: Data Summary and Implications

1. This analysis utilized the ARIMA model because there was no seasonality present which makes the ARIMA model a good fit.
2. We used this prediction algorithm to run the data through to give us the optimal prediction.
3. The forecast length is justified because the original data set is 2 years and we are predicting for the next future year. Looking at the upcoming years' predictions can assist us in making good business decisions.
4. The model evaluation procedure and error metric is RMSE of .568 which is not optimal as the closer to zero the better the score.
The annotated visualization of the forecast of the final model compared to the test set can be seen above.
Based on these findings the recommended course of action is to run additional tests to determine which variables will increase revenue over the next year.
